column28: Make all libraries fully accessible.  (Not all are)  Use system funding to help all libraries meet an OCPL "minimum standard" for facilities - study rooms, meeting rooms, space for children, etc.  Provide better physical descriptions and photos of interiors of libraries on main web page.  Have system develop a ranked priority for facilities improvements, including for suburban libraries.  Design for the future!  VR, AI, community service points and gathering spaces, etc.
column45: Spaces for activities like puzzles and video games
column46: Need increased staffing to actually do this, especially in small libraries.
column52: Staff diversity is low.  Some libraries come across as not particularly welcoming to new library users.  The programming really depends on what library you are close to.  Not enough space for art, design, informational programming.  I get a lot of information from using the internet independently, because the databases are not the easiest to use.  Libraries don't always collect non-fiction in enough depth, and non-fiction collection development is not coordinated across the system - so holds don't always work to get what you need.  ILL is not always the answer.  Not enough knowledge and celebration of different cultures, other than that group's month.  (African Americans in February, etc.)  This is true especially in suburban libraries.  Music and video collections not the most inclusive.  My needs for health information, financial information, and living as a senior are not really met, unless I have the time/transportation to go to a bunch of different libraries.
column53: Talk to non-users!  They are likely not answering this survey.  Go to the farmer's market, baseball games, schools, OCC, etc. where you can actually talk to a wide range of people.  to get a more representative sample of what people think.  Don't wait for people to come to the library - meet them where they are.  Do the demographics of the survey answers even match the community?  Make it easier for library patrons to suggest materials and programs, and share more information on programs between libraries.  Have more training for sub-groups like children's librarians.  System needs to be more cohesive.  Reach out to other library systems  to exchange ideas.  What are they doing to broaden their appeal?
column65: Provide centralized support for programming with unhoused persons, etc.  Very difficult to develop programs for all populations in isolation.
column67: Engagement of staff, willingness to try out new programming, different "vibes" in each library (also can be a weakness).  The inclusiveness for patrons outside the county.
column68: More connection with school districts across the county - should be several positions of librarians who work together with schools and school libraries - what curricula do they use?  What is their understanding/use of the science of reading?  How specifically can OCPL help parents and especially students with lower academic scores?  Bring back the bookmobiles going to city parks, perhaps with cooperative marketing with parks&rec staff.  Have artists-in-residence that teach library patrons on various things.  Do a whole-county newsletter that points out exactly how we are fulfilling our mission.  What exactly do we mean by "preparing our community for a bright future?"  The library's plan for doing the mission is unclear and not integrated with suburban library plans - a plan for just the city is not a plan for OCPL.  How are we creating opportunities?  What does that mean, and are all libraries on the same page as to what the opportunities are?  I am NOT saying that all libraries need to be identical, but I am saying we need to be closer so that substantial progress towards OCPL goals are happening in every library.  Some libraries (smaller) are going to need more support making that happen.  We need a more diverse staff in all areas.  We need to talk with community groups like Focus Greater Syracuse to get different ideas.  We need to really check the "vocational awe!"  We would be better off not trying to be everything for everyone.  Just because an idea is good and worthy, doesn't mean OCPL has to do it.

column27: A big trend is Baby Boomers retiring from full-time work and, because of inflation, looking for part-time work. I would like librarians to be able to have some kind of powerful system or approach to help, other than to say "Look on Indeed," which is what one librarian told me. Knitting groups and storytime are excellent, but how about the library sponsoring experts to hold a workshop to advise Boomers on how they can get part-time work. Or maybe the library can compile a part-time-jobs-for-retirees clearinghouse for all different kinds of part-time jobs. It would be fun for me--and other Boomers, I'm sure--to learn about jobs in fields that we have not immersed ourselves in for 43 years! Thank you if you can come up with some kind of program for retirees looking for part-time work.

column28: Libraries used to be quiet places to read and reflect. Now I notice (at least at my library which is Onondaga Free) people will be in the common seating areas that really should be for reading and quiet, interacting with one another very loudly and not at all attempting to be quiet or courteous of others who ARE trying to read quietly.  The children's spaces are where noisy children and parents should go. And if you're working on a project or some collaborative effort, go to a private room where you can talk as loudly as you want-not in the middle of the library or somewhere cozy that is clearly meant for quiet (like the lovely seating are near the fireplace at Onondaga Free. )I sound like an old lady, but honestly, our society is NEVER quiet and the library should still be a place where we can expect that.  Remember the days of librarians shushing people? Let's bring it back!!!!

column65: Hiring staff who are more outgoing.   Teach staff about what "customer service" means.   I previously worked several years at NOPL North Syracuse. We would greet everyone who came into the library so they knew they were welcome and that we notices them. Most often we got to know them by name. This helps people to feel seen. It's a common practice in the majority of retail shops. In the last seven years I have noticed a huge drop in customer service. No one greets you. No one smiles. No one interacts with you. Instead of feeling like you have entered a "community centered environment" you feel like you're not welcome. I've been to many of the city and suburban branches and the majority of them are as I describe... unfriendly, unwelcoming and act as though you are disturbing them when you do take the chance to approach them. To me... this is the saddest aspect of libraries today.

column28: Please remove computers from your children's sections. Many caregivers bring their children to get away from screens/tech. The world outside libraries is inundated with screens. They get them in school. Many parents use them as babysitters. They are everywhere, and many parents who take their kids to the library do so because they want their kids interacting with books, not screens. How many times have I said - and heard other parents say - "We're not here for screens. Leave the computer alone and pick out a book"? So many times! Some of the suburban libraries have their kids computers in a separate section from their children's book collection. This makes life easier for adults. I know you're going to say "but kids need the computers for school projects and educational activities." BS. SCSD gives almost no homework or book reports now. Tech is cheap. It's tech instruction, mindful parenting, and thoughtful human-to-human contact that's increasingly hard to come by in this day and age. In the meantime, please speed up your branch internet and wifi. The adults who do need to use tech and get assistance are often super frustrated by how slow and outdated that tech is. Maybe consider getting city library tech updated every few years on a regular schedule?

column53: I frequently am frustrated by the policy held by the county branches of withholding new releases from city branches. As an avid reader, I am often waiting on new book releases and tracking the books status in the library system. By now I know that the city branch I use will not have holds filled by county branches of new books, despite the books sitting idle on their shelves for weeks and months. Moreover, the city's copies of new books are often very delayed in being added to the system, so not only can I not get the unused county's copy of anew book, but no city copies are available at all.  I am also disappointed to see that some city branch libraries are considering closing at night, or lessening the amount of nights available to the community. Libraries are important public spaces, especially for teens and youth. We should expand access to the library at night so that young people can have safe spaces to meet.

column28: I really don't want the Hazard library changed. It now has historic architectural value. Warmer lighting in the community room would make events much more pleasant. The elevator should be fixed. More easy chairs in the reading corner window would be nice. Remove the study carrel from the reading room and relocate all study carrels to the adult side.
column46: From my perspective, based on program offerings, OCPL is entirely unaware there are men ages 21-50 years old in Syracuse.
column52: Collections are a bit heavy on strict genre material like murder mysteries and cowboy romances, which surely are popular with some people, but not me. New books *do* include material that interests me, but less of the genre stuff and more of what I like would be nice.
column53: I like science and history for the lay-person and more literary style and historical fiction. There is a good selection of that material, but since you asked, more of it would be nice.
column65: Not much non-English material, but I don't know how much that is due to limited publication, limited staff language ability, or reflecting the size of the non-English speaking population in our area. Efforts to include LGBTQ are very clear. Access for "unhoused/homeless" is high enough at some locations that it might deter some for using the library for reading and learning. The library does not need to act as a halfway house.
column67: The collections are very good and that is key. The inter-branch hold service is excellent and *actually* give me access to the entire system like it is one library. Inter-library loan for university type material is good when I need something outside the system.
column68: The main "question mark" in my mind is why don't I see advertising for the library out in the community at places like the grocery store or cafes? I don't know what is going on with the library unless I actively look for it. Even then the web site does not present things well. A text/email notification system would be nice. I don't want spam, but new book descriptions or event notifications for my selected interests would be a nice feature.

column68: Make it possible to access databases like Ancestry.com and the nonprofit resource library online (not just in the Central Branch). Work to get access to more news sources and promote them, help patrons understand options for getting news when they can't afford to get beyond paywalls. Help bridge the information gap and teach more tech skills (e.g., how to use Excel). Offer more "tech help" time where librarians or agencies like Literacy CNY set up tables and offer assistance with devices they don't understand. Create more spaces for community gathering  (like Liverpool's big community room). The future needs it!
